According to recommendations from @Charles Duffy, I traced the source code of `cmd.Run()` and found that:

```golang

type SysProcAttr struct {
	UidMappings  []SysProcIDMap // User ID mappings for user namespaces.
	GidMappings  []SysProcIDMap // Group ID mappings for user namespaces.
	// GidMappingsEnableSetgroups enabling setgroups syscall.
	// If false, then setgroups syscall will be disabled for the child process.
	// This parameter is no-op if GidMappings == nil. Otherwise for unprivileged
	// users this should be set to false for mappings work.
	GidMappingsEnableSetgroups bool
}
```
Thus, if the value of `GidMappingsEnableSetgroups` is `false` as default, the child process `justiceInit` will have no permission to use `setgroups` syscall regardless of whether it has root privileges. 

As a result, when I set `cmd.SysProcAttr.GidMappingsEnableSetgroups` as `true` in the function `main` as follows, it works!

```golang
cmd.Stdin = os.Stdin
cmd.Stdout = os.Stdout
cmd.Stderr = os.Stderr
cmd.SysProcAttr = &amp;syscall.SysProcAttr{
    // ...
    GidMappingsEnableSetgroups: true,
}
```

